    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p>Not previously published.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#_μος"><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><seg part="F">μος</seg></name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#_ης" type="patronymic"><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><seg part="F"><supplied reason="lost">ε</supplied>υς</seg></name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>mos fils de <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>ès.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>mos son of <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>es.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>mos figlio di <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>es.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Although broken off below, the stone seems not to have been inscribed below line 2. A name in <foreign xml:lang="grc">-δαμος</foreign> or <foreign xml:lang="grc">-τιμος</foreign>
                would be plausible for line 1 whereas line 2 should bear a father's name ending in <foreign xml:lang="grc">-ης</foreign>, perhaps in <foreign xml:lang="grc">-κλῆς</foreign>. No 
                choice is possible amongst a lot of possibilities. As we have only a fragment and as the exact findspot is unknown, it is impossible to decide whether this inscription was funerary 
                or honorific.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
